Architecture Explanation – GroupExpense
The GroupExpense system follows a client–server layered architecture,
consisting of three main layers: Client (Frontend), Server (Backend), and Database.
The system is containerized using Docker for consistent deployment.
2.1 Client Layer (Frontend)
The client layer is built using React (Vite) and is responsible for user inter-
action. Users access the application through a web browser.
Responsibilities:
• Provides user interface (Dashboard, Add Expense, Groups)
• Sends requests to the backend
• Displays responses to the user
Communication:
• Uses REST API (HTTP requests) to communicate with the backend
2.2 Server Layer (Backend)
The server layer is implemented using Node.js with Express. It handles the
core business logic of the system.
Main Modules:
• Auth Module: Handles user authentication (login, signup)
• Expense Module: Manages expense creation and splitting
• Balance Module: Calculates and updates balances
Functions:
1
• Receives requests from frontend
• Processes business logic
• Sends responses back to frontend
2.3 Database Layer
The database layer uses PostgreSQL to store persistent data.
Stored Data:
• Users
• Groups
• Expenses
• Transactions
Communication:
• Backend interacts with the database using Prisma ORM
• Converts application code into SQL queries
2.4 DevOps / Containerization
Each component runs inside a separate Docker container.
• Frontend Container
• Backend Container
• Database Container
Benefits:
• Consistent development environment
• Easy setup using Docker Compose
• Independent deployment of components
2.5 System Workflow
1. User performs an action (e.g., adds expense)
2. Frontend sends request to backend via REST API
3. Backend processes the request
4. Backend interacts with the database
5. Database returns data
6. Backend sends response to frontend
7. Frontend updates the user interface
2.6 Advantages
• Loose coupling between layers
• High scalability
• Easy maintenance due to modular design
• Flexibility to replace or upgrade components
